article.headline: Arizona State 68, USC 65
article.story: LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The youthful Arizona State Sun Devils have found a way to lose several times in the late going this season. On Saturday, they found a way to win. Freshman Jeff Pendergraph had 15 points and seven rebounds, Kevin Kruger scored five of his 14 points in the last 43½ seconds on free throws, and the last-place Sun Devils held off Southern California 68-65. Sead Odzic made two of USC's four 3-pointers in the last 44 seconds, but his second came with less than half-a-second remaining. After the Trojans took a timeout, ASU was able to inbound the ball and time expired. "To come out and execute and finish a game like this is huge for the kids," ASU coach Rob Evans said. "It's just a great confidence-booster. We really got after them defensively. We didn't give them any second-chance points. "They are fighting to get to the NCAA tournament. We're fighting to win every game we can." ASU snapped a four-game losing streak and won just its second Pac-10 game of the season. The Sun Devils also ended a four-game losing streak to USC and beat the Trojans in Los Angeles for only the second time in 10 games. "Every time we lose, it's ourselves making mistakes," Pendergraph said. "We limit the mistakes, we win." Serge Angounou had 11 points and 10 rebounds, freshman Sylvester Seay also scored 11 points, and Bryson Krueger added 10 for the Sun Devils (8-12, 2-9), who shot 50 percent and outrebounded USC 37-21. "It's a team we don't match up well with," USC coach Tim Floyd said. "Our inability to rebound has been a problem all year long. I knew Arizona State was going to win some more games this year. It's too bad we had to pay the price. You've got to credit their defense." Gabe Pruitt led USC (15-7, 6-5) with 22 points and five rebounds. Nick Young added 12 for the Trojans, who shot 12-of-29 from 3-point range and 11-of 24 from inside the arc. ASU went ahead for good by outscoring USC 21-4 in the last 7½ minutes of the first half for a 40-29 lead. Kruger scored nine points during the spurt, making three 3-pointers without a miss. The Trojans scored the first seven points of the second half to move within four points. The Sun Devils extended their lead to 10 before USC went on a 11-4 run to make it 52-49. But that was as close as the Trojans would get. Angounou scored the game's next five points, and Krueger added a 3-pointer with 4:37 remaining to make it 60-51. USC's Abdoulaye Ndiaye dunked with 4:11 to play, but neither team scored again Krueger made two free throws with 56.7 seconds left, giving ASU a 62-53 lead. The Trojans made four 3-pointers in the last 44 seconds, but it wasn't enough. Pruitt made four 3-pointers and Young added two in the first 10 minutes, accounting for all but two of USC's points as the Trojans took a 20-12 lead. ASU adjusted its defense at that stage, and Pruitt didn't score again until making another 3-pointer three minutes into the second half. "They kind of picked it up, changed their defensive game plan, limited my touches a little bit," Pruitt said. "I knew this would be a tough game. Their record doesn't mean anything. Pretty much all of their games have come down to the wire." Evans said the key to defending Pruitt was getting to him quickly when he got the ball. "Our guys got out and got to him, made him put it on the floor," Evans said. "He's a lot different player when he has to put it on the floor." Young sat out the last 10:46 of the first half after picking up his third foul, and ASU took command with the 6-foot-6 sophomore on the bench. "We didn't get to the foul line that much like we usually do," said Young, noting the Trojans were 7-of-9 from the foul line while the Sun Devils were 16-of-23. ASU's 40 points at halftime were its highest total at that stage since the Sun Devils scored 48 in a season-opening 82-62 victory over Southern Utah. The Trojans beat the Sun Devils 66-65 in Arizona last month on Lodrick Stewart's 3-pointer with 2.1 seconds left. Stewart, averaging 12.6 points, had only seven in this game.
